      passage: `In Ojibwe, an Indigenous language from the Great Lakes region of what are now the United States and Canada, <em>w&acirc;sa</em> means &ldquo;far,&rdquo; whereas <em>wa-w&acirc;sa</em> means &ldquo;far apart.&rdquo; This phenomenon, in which an element of a root word is repeated, sometimes with modification, within another word that is related to the root word, is called reduplication. In this case, the element &ldquo;w&aacute;&rdquo; in <em>w&acirc;sa</em> gets repeated in <em>wa-w&acirc;sa</em>. There are many examples of this type of reduplication in Ojibwe.`,
